<subSubSection id="C31C6500197AFFBD6A8BA1F572D6FD24" pageId="90" pageNumber="91" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph id="8BB9368B197AFFBD6A8BA1F571E5FE38" blockId="90.[189,457,402,428]" box="[189,457,402,428]" pageId="90" pageNumber="91">
<heading id="D0F181E7197AFFBD6A8BA1F571E5FE38" bold="true" box="[189,457,402,428]" fontSize="11" level="3" pageId="90" pageNumber="91" reason="3">
<emphasis id="B972EA99197AFFBD6A8BA1F571E5FE38" bold="true" box="[189,457,402,428]" pageId="90" pageNumber="91">Differential diagnosis</emphasis>
</heading>
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8BB9368B197AFFBD6A8BA1A672D6FD24" blockId="90.[189,1399,449,688]" pageId="90" pageNumber="91">
<taxonomicName id="4C064D08197AFFBD6A8BA1A67274FE4F" authority="Steenis &amp; Hippa &amp; Mutin, 2018" authorityName="Steenis &amp; Hippa &amp; Mutin" authorityYear="2018" box="[189,600,449,475]" class="Insecta" family="Syrphidae" genus="Sphegina" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="90" pageNumber="91" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="hamulata" status="sp. nov." subGenus="Asiosphegina">
<emphasis id="B972EA99197AFFBD6A8BA1A67274FE4F" box="[189,600,449,475]" italics="true" pageId="90" pageNumber="91">Sphegina (Asiosphegina) hamulata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel id="A24157E2197AFFBD6868A1A67294FE4F" box="[606,696,449,475]" pageId="90" pageNumber="91" rank="species">sp. nov.</taxonomicNameLabel>
is not especially similar to any other known 
<taxonomicName id="4C064D08197AFFBD6E88A1A67507FE4F" authorityName="Meigen" authorityYear="1822" box="[1214,1323,449,475]" class="Insecta" family="Syrphidae" genus="Sphegina" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="90" pageNumber="91" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B972EA99197AFFBD6E88A1A67507FE4F" box="[1214,1323,449,475]" italics="true" pageId="90" pageNumber="91">Sphegina</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and is easily distinguished by the characters mentioned in the key. It resembles a number of those species which have strong setae posteriorly on male sternum IV, but the setae are all pale (in the other species at least a number of them are black). In addition, the sternum is almost symmetrical (distinctly asymmetrical), except for the submembranous flange posteriorly from the setae which is situated on the left side. The asymmetrical surstyli with the right-side one wider than the left-side one occur commonly in this group. The narrow hook-shaped left surstylus is unique.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="C31C6500197AFFBD6A8BA2B072ABFCD0" pageId="90" pageNumber="91" type="etymology">
<paragraph id="8BB9368B197AFFBD6A8BA2B07168FD65" blockId="90.[189,324,727,753]" box="[189,324,727,753]" pageId="90" pageNumber="91">
<heading id="D0F181E7197AFFBD6A8BA2B07168FD65" bold="true" box="[189,324,727,753]" fontSize="11" level="3" pageId="90" pageNumber="91" reason="3">
<emphasis id="B972EA99197AFFBD6A8BA2B07168FD65" bold="true" box="[189,324,727,753]" pageId="90" pageNumber="91">Etymology</emphasis>
</heading>
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8BB9368B197AFFBD6A8BA36172ABFCD0" blockId="90.[189,1399,774,836]" pageId="90" pageNumber="91">
The specific epithet is from the Latin ‘ 
<taxonomicName id="4C064D08197AFFBD68AAA3617327FCB4" authorityName="Steenis &amp; Hippa &amp; Mutin" authorityYear="2018" box="[668,779,774,800]" class="Insecta" family="Syrphidae" genus="Sphegina" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="90" pageNumber="91" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="hamulata">
<emphasis id="B972EA99197AFFBD68AAA3617327FCB4" box="[668,779,774,800]" italics="true" pageId="90" pageNumber="91">hamulata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
’, meaning ‘with a little hook’ and referring to the posteriorly hooked right side surstylus.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
